headline: Mother seen dancing to Backstreet Boys during snowy, gridlocked traffic
subHeadline: During gridlocked traffic, daughter records her mother dancing in the street to Backstreet Boys.

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello, everyone. I'm Dana Perino, along with Dan Bongino, Marie Harf, Jesse Watters, and Greg Gutfeld.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: It's 5 o'clock in New York City, and this is The Five.  The Senate passing a bill to reopen the government for three weeks, it now heads over to the House for a vote expected tonight, President Trump announcing a deal to end the 35-day partial government shutdown. The bill doesn't include wall funding, but the president vows to keep fighting for it.

utterances.speaker: PRESIDENT DONALD TRUMP
utterances.sentences: Wall should not be controversial. That's why most of the Democrats in Congress have voted in the past for bills that include walls and physical barriers and very powerful fences.  If we don't get a fair deal from Congress, the government will either shut down or on February 15th, again, or I will use the powers afforded to me under the laws and the constitution of the United States to address this emergency.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer placing the shutdown blame on President Trump.

utterances.speaker: SEN. CHUCK SCHUMER, D-N.Y., SENATE MINORITY LEADER
utterances.sentences: Hopefully now the president has learned his lesson. We cannot, cannot ever hold American workers hostage again. We hope -- make it clear to the president -- to the public, that the president was the one in charge of the shutdown.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And House Speaker Nancy Pelosi saying once the government is back open, she is willing to work with the president to set a date for the State of the Union. So, Jesse, we are back where we began before the shutdown even started. So now, there's three weeks to go.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, HOST
utterances.sentences: Yeah. Well, thank God it's over right now. I think Trump lost the battle, so he's got to win the war. He's got to get something out of an emergency declaration. And if he doesn't get something done there he has to flip the House --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Do you think he will?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Do you think he will do a national emergency --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, because I know -- I still think they're too far apart, so he's got to do the national emergency. He's got to get reelected so then maybe he has more of a mandate, more political capital to get the wall funding.  But at this point, the last shutdown was the Schumer shutdown and that was perfectly teed up for the president because Schumer was protecting illegal immigrants over veterans getting paid. This dynamic was totally different because the president took ownership of the shutdown, and then it was the border wall funding versus American federal workers getting paid. And that really wasn't a very good dynamic for him, and Pelosi just obstructed and the media helped her, so she just waited him out.  Five weeks later and people didn't get paid and there's no border wall, so where do we stand? I don't know. It just seems like the airplane situation, the callous statement from the commerce secretary, the FBI director coming out and saying reopening this thing, that was what cranked up the pressure in order for the president to change gears.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: So, I think, sometimes leaders have to do that, right? They have to say, OK, well, this isn't working. We're going to have to switch gears.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: What he said. He lost the battle but the war is still going. Look, OK, this is tiresome, it's boring, and it's infuriating. And it's frustrating because this isn't just pure politics. This is a petulant reaction to a phenomenon, right? Walls are normal, we have walls. They'd be willing to spend more money that's he's actually asking for, so it's not about immigration at all. It's about Trump. And Trump, whether you like him or you hate him, he's the phenomenon of the last two years that has created this kind of animosity, right?  These people -- I don't see any compromise coming in this, because if the Dems compromise, the media will just rip it to shreds. This is a personal vendetta against Trump. They're putting now -- they're putting security and they're putting the government employees, you know, to the side in favor of their own personal hatred of Trump. That's why I find it so boring and so tiresome because I know this isn't going to change. We're going to get at least -- we're going to get two more years, possibly six more years of this.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And, I wanted to ask you, Dan, we're back where we were before.

utterances.speaker: DAN BONGINO, HOST
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Do the president's supporters not do him any favors by pushing him into fights that he can't possibly win?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: No, because he can win this. I have two points on this. First, I thought Schumer handled that awfully. Nancy Pelosi clearly understood she had to tow the middle on that while giving that press conference.  Schumer came off like a total snake. You know, Trump gives -- capitulates some of the Democrats' demands and comes to the table, opens up the government, and what Schumer do? He comes out in twice repeats the point, we taught you, you learned a lesson. There was no need for that. I think the president --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: You don't need to be a sore loser.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: No, no. The president should pull that deal off of the table right now and say, good luck, Chuck. Knock it out now (ph). And the second point is, listen, politics is all about a political bank account, right? Having -- I don't mean money. I mean building a political capital. The president now has three weeks to race to the finish line to get a deal his base can really coalesce around. You know, it wasn't a great day today for the president. Wasn't a great day --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: But if he doesn't do that and he does a national emergency, then you think the base would be fine with that?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: I'm not a huge fan of the national emergency plan. I'm always afraid of centralizing power in government in any office even when it's a Republican president. I refuse to be a hypocrite on that. But having said that, the Congress did delegate him that power, and would it be illegal to do it? I don't agree with it, but it is there.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: He could. It's an option.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: And he's base, you know, may, in fact, likes something like that. By the time he builds a lot of that wall, by the way, and it makes it through the courts, he could build a whole boat load of wall before he even gets there.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And the reelection will -- completed by then.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Likely.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Marie, the president even said in the Rose Garden today, we don't need 2,000 miles of a concrete wall. I've already said that. The Democrats have already voted for barriers, so really what are we fighting over at this point?

utterances.speaker: MARIE HARF, HOST
utterances.sentences: I think Donald Trump or, at least, his political teams saw what happened in the Senate yesterday that Mitch McConnell, I think, was very shrewd in putting forward both bills and showing -- demonstrating to the president that his plan had fewer votes, actually, than, essentially, what they've ended up passing today. ACR, to fight over this for a few more weeks.  You know, the president yesterday at this time, the White House was saying we will do a C.R. for three weeks with a very large down payment. Well, the president agreed to do that with no down payment today. So, he, I think, saw the political writing on the wall that for the Oval Office address and all of the way he's been messaging this, the numbers haven't really moved and he's been getting blamed. I actually think that given the fact the Democrats feel like they won this round, they will feel empowered to make, possibly, a compromise.  So something like I said yesterday, let's say $5 billion that includes barriers where experts say they're needed. And the president today talking about an experts, sort of group, I like that too. I think that's like some sort of commission --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: That's Greg idea.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No, I stole that from Scott Adams. That was a Scott Adams idea that I stole.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: But I think the Democrats may feel a little bit empowered to say, OK, now, we are going to compromise on this if we get DACA, if we get TPS. I also think the other lesson I took from this, Nancy Pelosi is someone I have underestimated as a Democrat. I wanted someone else to be Speaker. I underestimated her ability to win role back. And I underestimated her ability to go toe-to-toe with Trump. And she showed him that things are different in Washington now. And that's what's going to be like.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know what --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: She showed strength there.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: -- they totally non-sexist -- they're both workhorses. They're old workhorses. They're both similar in age, right? She's been around. He's been around. Bam. So, what are they fighting for? You know what it is? It's like the ugly vase in a divorce. No, when they were married -- when they were married, nobody wanted the vase, right? That's what immigration is. Nobody wants to talk about it. And then they get in a fight and it's like they're fighting over -- they don't even like the vase, but they're going to fight over it even though it's not a big deal. But I do think to the point that you brought up about the panel of experts and engineers, this -- objective group --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: -- is a step forward, which means for the war, it could win -- he could win this using that as a weapon.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I volunteered to be one of the expert on that panel. What's so funny?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, I mean, what could go wrong there?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I'm Watters and this is my wall.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right, we're going to move on. A wild scene outside the courthouse after Roger Stone's indictment, hear his response to the charges, next.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: A media circus outside of a federal courthouse in Florida, today, after Roger Stone was indicted on seven charges including obstruction, making false statements and witness tampering. The White House saying Stone arrest has nothing to do with the president, and reiterated there's no Russian collusion, Trump's former advisor addressing reporters after his court hearing.

utterances.speaker: ROGER STONE, FORMER TRUMP ADVISER
utterances.sentences: I am falsely accused of making false statements during my testimony to the House Intelligence Committee. I will plead not guilty to these charges. I will defeat them in court. I believe this is a politically motivated investigation. I have made it clear, I will not testify against the president, because I would have to bear false witness against him.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: The president and some conservatives questioning how CNN found out about the pre-dawn FBI raid on Stone's house that was caught on exclusive video which we are watching right here. OK, a lot to unpack in this indictment and what happened today. But, Greg, I want to start with you. You have a theory on the pre-dawn raid --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. Everyone is wondering who tipped off CNN.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Stone did. The worst thing that could happen to him is to be arrested in total darkness. His whole life is a spectacle. He loved it. He'd been bating people to arrest him. What did he say? Come after me, lip-tards, which I think you can't say. I'm not sure. But also exposure like that creates sympathy and attention which he enjoys. And, come on, he looked great which meant he knew it was coming. He had a nice polo shirt. He probably even brushed his teeth. This is the thing about these pre-dawn raids that I don't like, I'm not a morning person. It is cruel and unusual punishment to do it so early in the morning. You haven't brushed your teeth. You haven't had your bacon. You haven't done your stuff. And you just need to get ready. So -- this is to my bigger thought.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: It gets bigger than that?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. Stone is about creating a spectacle about his life. I don't believe he ever had much of any influence on the campaign at all. But he like to portray it as much because that's what -- he like to portray who he is. His M.O. has always been about exaggerating his influence, I think.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: If I ever had pre-dawn raid, I'll be ready to go.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I'm like -- the ponytail, you know, the other clothes.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: You have the clothes on. So, Dana, in this indictment the paragraph that they're focusing on is where it said a senior Trump campaign official was directed to contact Stone about any additional WikiLeaks releases and what other damaging information WikiLeaks had regarding the Clinton campaign. Stone there after told the Trump campaign about future releases of damaging material. Of course, WikiLeaks has been called by Mike Pompeo a non-state hostile intelligence service.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: So there's another part where, apparently, somebody from the Trump campaign then calls him afterwards and said good job.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: OK. So --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: So unpack that for us.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, I don't know. I'm just reading it, too. On the three indictments he's got like the lying to Congress, the false statements to the FBI, and obstruction. And just for my time DOJ what I remember -- if I'm happy right here, that you lead with the thing that you think you have the strongest evidence for, so lying to Congress. One of the reason I think they have that if you read the indictment is, apparently, while he is trying to intimidate witnesses or obstruction, whatever, like he's saying, oh, no, I've never texted them, while he's texting right under the table. So --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: And the FBI has all those texts.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: They have it all. They have it all.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: So, Dan, I have a feeling you're going to say this is a process crime.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: I am --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: So, but let me ask you a question --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Well, forget about no collusion.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: The process of lying, the substance of what he lied about I think should matter and is an interesting development in WikiLeaks working with the campaign through Stone. How do you respond to what seems pretty damming in this?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Well, I've been a Federal agent. People lie for all kinds of reasons. They make mistakes all the time. Sometimes people misremember. Sometime they overtly lie because they don't know what the government has and they're trying to protect themselves. But I find something really interesting you've said, I love to get your take on here, because Jessica Tarlov, who I like as well. She is the reason I'm outnumbered (ph) said the same thing. She finds this senior campaign official, I wrote this down, who communicated with a non-state intel actor to be unsavory. Well, that's fascinating because Hillary Clinton actually communicated with foreign intel people, notably Christopher Steele, who said in an on the record deposition that he got his intel from Russian intel. So I just want -- I just want to be clear, no, serious question --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes, what-about-ism. I love it.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Whataboutism --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Marie, seriously, do we have principles here or not? Is communicating with unsavory actors associated with intelligence agents a bad thing or not?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: So --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: No, no, no. It's a yes or no. This is really simple.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: No, but you're setting it up as yes or no to try to make a point. Let me answer the substance of your question. If there's an indictment that lays out in detail that a Hillary Clinton campaign official was working --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: He swore on the record --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: -- was working with WikiLeaks --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: he gave a sworn deposition in a court case in London.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Sorry, Michael Steele. Oh, my God.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I'm not a fan of him either.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: If he had some sort of communication with Hillary Clinton herself, I'm happy to see that.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Our team paid --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: But --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: You have to know this.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Dan, I want you to answer for this case and not always make it about Hillary.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: I know, I wrote it down, with a non-state intelligence person is a bad thing, but with actual Russian intelligence --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Jesse, can you give us substantive answer that doesn't bring up Hillary but just answer this?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Substantive? Here's what I would say --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: How do you explain this?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I didn't -- I heard the lock him up chants in the background, I found that really unbecoming.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You know, unsavory, uncivilized --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Innocent until proven guilty.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Right, innocent until proven guilty. And use your own slogans, by the way. Those are our slogans. And I would not have gone out with a double peace sign, Nixon move, that's not maybe the best look. Would have flipped the collar up if you're going to rock the polo, just a little piece of advice there. I notice that --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You're not helping him.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: He also called himself a tri-sexual. Now I found out that means he's tried everything, which, you know, to each his own. That's fine. I agree with Greg, the pre-dawn raid seems a little heavy-handed, like he was -- this wasn't the Waco compound. This was a three bedroom apartment in Fort Lauderdale. They've expect he was going to come out like Scarface and start mowing down people with a machine gun? No. I've also -- my sources are telling me that CNN was tipped off. And my sources, or Lanny Davis and BuzzFeed, so there you go.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: I clearly have no idea how to respond to most of what you've said -- .

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Because he was on Dancing with the Stars.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Wait a minute, that's what he's got to do, Dancing with the Stars. Was he already --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: It's the only way. Well, he's going to be on Tucker tonight.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Who was also on Dancing with the Stars?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Nicely done.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Guess what? I'm going to be on Tucker tonight.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Everybody is on Tucker.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: We will -- Roger Stone is coming up, I think, to Washington, D.C. to be arraigned up here, so we will see that next week. See if he's still on a polo shirt, maybe he found one of his suits. OK, up next, Elizabeth Warren joining Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez and calling for new taxes on the super-rich, we will have the details. Plus, President Trump's response.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: As Venezuela socialist system crumbles, some liberals here in the U.S. are pushing the same failed policies, 2020 Democratic-hopeful Elizabeth Warren is the latest calling for a wealth tax on ultra- millionaires with more than $50 million. This comes after Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez's proposal for a 70 percent tax rate on the wealthy. President Trump blasting these progressive ideas.

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.sentences: Well, look at Venezuela, it's a very sad situation. That's what socialism gets you when they want to raise your taxes to 70 percent. You know it's interesting, I've been watching our opponents, our future opponents talking about 70 percent. Number one, they can't do it for 70 percent, got to be probably twice that number. But -- maybe more importantly, what happens is you literally have to study and take a look at what has happened to Venezuela.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Hmm.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Yes, Dan?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: You just knew. You just -- I didn't have to say anything. We've got a ESP mind language.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: I've just knew it.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: So here's my question for you. You are the representative Democrat on the panel here today. Democrats seem to love this idea of, you know, confiscating money from people, even though they've shown no evidence --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Jesse, gave me --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: I know. I was here --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: But here's my question, why don't Democrats just lead by example, John Kerry, Ocasio-Cortez, Barack Obama, Joe Biden, Hillary, and others, and just voluntarily give up extra money to the government. You can do it. It's not illegal. You can donate. Why don't they do that?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: I think -- because that's a silly idea.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: But why? Why is it a silly idea?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: Because there's a large -- the point that Elizabeth Warren is making -- and, by the way, she's not my preferred candidate for president. She's probably not my top ten. But the point she's making is raising an issue that there -- the fact that we, in this country, the richest country on earth, the best country on earth we would all say, we still have not figured out how to solve what is a problem with economic inequality. And I'm not saying her plan is the right one, but at least she's getting people talking about it. And the fact that the president's tax plan was tilted more towards corporations, particularly corporations, but also towards higher brackets. There are middle-class people in this country who could use some relief. So, I'm not sure her plan is the right one, but she's dismissing it by saying, oh, Democrats just wants to be Venezuela, or why isn't John Kerry pay more isn't engaging with the really big problem we have in the country. Why more people aren't getting into the middle class can afford health care, can afford college. That's a bigger problem than saying, but Venezuela.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I disagree.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Greg, I know this is a sensitive topic.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I am going to call the --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Is this a utopia fallacy here, though? That inequality in some utopian planet doesn't exist. Inequality is a problem, so how do you fix it? Nobody is --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: What's better, though?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No. Ok, first of all, Warren, again, is a copycat. First she tried to rip off the Cherokees, now she's trying to rip off AOC. Come up with your own ideas. OK. Everybody is talking about inequality but what they're doing is -- they're not talking about what makes America so unique in this capital -- this free market society mobility. So, even though there's inequality, the inequality may look like it's stagnant, but within that people are constantly moving. So somebody who at the top 10 percent a decade ago may not be in the top 10 percent, you know, now. And there's people constantly moving up. I mean, I started making nothing in 1988, and it took me a long-ass-time to get here, excuse the language. But it frustrates me because everybody looks at people who are wealthy and they assumed that they were always wealthy. That's not the case. Every single wealthy person borrowing -- people who get it from their mommy and daddy, it's going up the ladder. And it's the mobility that people keep forgetting. The thing that frustrates me, too, when you ask people who are appalled about raising taxes, a lot of them don't have skin in the game. So it's easy to say tax that guy. The 10 percent already pay the majority of the taxes and there's a large portion of Americans who don't pay any taxes. So it's very easy to say I'm for raising taxes when you have no skin in the game.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Dana, didn't they try this before, the Democrats, Walter Mondale, Michael Dukakis, his far-left lurch? And then you have Bill Clinton, the Democrat leadership committee came in and say, listen, this isn't working. America is an entrepreneurial country. Generally, don't like this big government thing. I mean, I don't get, like, why they don't see this as a failure?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And then, Reagan, of course, you saw what was possible then with that kind of policy. I like that we're having this debate because I think we need to have it. As Karl Rove has written younger people who say they want socialism, you should take them seriously and explained to them what this is all about. I think one of the things on inequality is where you are concerned that there will be social instability because of it, right? It's because there's going to be too much between the haves and the have-nots and that's going to create more social instability and that could lead to something that none of us want. The problem is, is that they're using -- they're inciting the passions of social instability and inequality in order to get there. And not making a point, like Greg was making, that your opportunity, though, is what should be there. I think President Trump has a strong argument to make on this case. Arguably, I think, he was elected more on his economic policies than the wall. I think that he had a good point -- he's got a point to make about unemployment numbers. You can say that these tax cuts are for the rich, but you cannot argue that the unemployment didn't get better and that wages started to go up. There were impacts, good ones from his policies.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.sentences: Jesse, don't you find it odd on Dana's point that inequality is the highest in socialist countries where the socialist - the government has everything and the people starve to death like that's kind of an odd argument to me.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I always say to myself --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Why should I give the government more of my heart and money when if they just waste it on pork and corruption. Here is a great example. The Federal government spent $3 million to study lesbian obesity. Now, my gut instinct tells me this, lesbians are obese probably for the same reason straight people are obese. They eat too much and they don't exercise enough. I just saved us $3 million. So right there, we are wasting money. We have enough money and you can also raise taxes to 90% and you still can't pay for socialism. The universal healthcare thing cost $40 trillion and I know math is hard, but it doesn't exist that pot of money. And if you guys were to raise ...

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: But it exists and for the wall?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: The wall is $5 billion, this is $40 trillion, see what I said, math is hard.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.sentences: It is still real money, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS

utterances.utterance: Hello, everyone. I'm Dana Perino, along with Dan Bongino, Marie Harf, Jesse Watters, and Greg Gutfeld.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, HOST
utterances.utterance: Hello.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It's 5 o'clock in New York City, and this is The Five. The Senate passing a bill to reopen the government for three weeks, it now heads over to the House for a vote expected tonight, President Trump announcing a deal to end the 35-day partial government shutdown. The bill doesn't include wall funding, but the president vows to keep fighting for it.

utterances.speaker: PRESIDENT DONALD TRUMP
utterances.utterance: Wall should not be controversial. That's why most of the Democrats in Congress have voted in the past for bills that include walls and physical barriers and very powerful fences. If we don't get a fair deal from Congress, the government will either shut down or on February 15th, again, or I will use the powers afforded to me under the laws and the constitution of the United States to address this emergency.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer placing the shutdown blame on President Trump.

utterances.speaker: SEN. CHUCK SCHUMER, D-N.Y., SENATE MINORITY LEADER
utterances.utterance: Hopefully now the president has learned his lesson. We cannot, cannot ever hold American workers hostage again. We hope -- make it clear to the president -- to the public, that the president was the one in charge of the shutdown.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And House Speaker Nancy Pelosi saying once the government is back open, she is willing to work with the president to set a date for the State of the Union. So, Jesse, we are back where we began before the shutdown even started. So now, there's three weeks to go.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, HOST
utterances.utterance: Yeah. Well, thank God it's over right now. I think Trump lost the battle, so he's got to win the war. He's got to get something out of an emergency declaration. And if he doesn't get something done there he has to flip the House --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Do you think he will?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Do you think he will do a national emergency --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, because I know -- I still think they're too far apart, so he's got to do the national emergency. He's got to get reelected so then maybe he has more of a mandate, more political capital to get the wall funding. But at this point, the last shutdown was the Schumer shutdown and that was perfectly teed up for the president because Schumer was protecting illegal immigrants over veterans getting paid. This dynamic was totally different because the president took ownership of the shutdown, and then it was the border wall funding versus American federal workers getting paid. And that really wasn't a very good dynamic for him, and Pelosi just obstructed and the media helped her, so she just waited him out. Five weeks later and people didn't get paid and there's no border wall, so where do we stand? I don't know. It just seems like the airplane situation, the callous statement from the commerce secretary, the FBI director coming out and saying reopening this thing, that was what cranked up the pressure in order for the president to change gears.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: So, I think, sometimes leaders have to do that, right? They have to say, OK, well, this isn't working. We're going to have to switch gears.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What he said. He lost the battle but the war is still going. Look, OK, this is tiresome, it's boring, and it's infuriating. And it's frustrating because this isn't just pure politics. This is a petulant reaction to a phenomenon, right? Walls are normal, we have walls. They'd be willing to spend more money that's he's actually asking for, so it's not about immigration at all. It's about Trump. And Trump, whether you like him or you hate him, he's the phenomenon of the last two years that has created this kind of animosity, right? These people -- I don't see any compromise coming in this, because if the Dems compromise, the media will just rip it to shreds. This is a personal vendetta against Trump. They're putting now -- they're putting security and they're putting the government employees, you know, to the side in favor of their own personal hatred of Trump. That's why I find it so boring and so tiresome because I know this isn't going to change. We're going to get at least -- we're going to get two more years, possibly six more years of this.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And, I wanted to ask you, Dan, we're back where we were before.

utterances.speaker: DAN BONGINO, HOST
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Do the president's supporters not do him any favors by pushing him into fights that he can't possibly win?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: No, because he can win this. I have two points on this. First, I thought Schumer handled that awfully. Nancy Pelosi clearly understood she had to tow the middle on that while giving that press conference. Schumer came off like a total snake. You know, Trump gives -- capitulates some of the Democrats' demands and comes to the table, opens up the government, and what Schumer do? He comes out in twice repeats the point, we taught you, you learned a lesson. There was no need for that. I think the president --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You don't need to be a sore loser.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: No, no. The president should pull that deal off of the table right now and say, good luck, Chuck. Knock it out now (ph). And the second point is, listen, politics is all about a political bank account, right? Having -- I don't mean money. I mean building a political capital. The president now has three weeks to race to the finish line to get a deal his base can really coalesce around. You know, it wasn't a great day today for the president. Wasn't a great day --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But if he doesn't do that and he does a national emergency, then you think the base would be fine with that?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: I'm not a huge fan of the national emergency plan. I'm always afraid of centralizing power in government in any office even when it's a Republican president. I refuse to be a hypocrite on that. But having said that, the Congress did delegate him that power, and would it be illegal to do it? I don't agree with it, but it is there.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: He could. It's an option.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: And he's base, you know, may, in fact, likes something like that. By the time he builds a lot of that wall, by the way, and it makes it through the courts, he could build a whole boat load of wall before he even gets there.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And the reelection will -- completed by then.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Likely.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Marie, the president even said in the Rose Garden today, we don't need 2,000 miles of a concrete wall. I've already said that. The Democrats have already voted for barriers, so really what are we fighting over at this point?

utterances.speaker: MARIE HARF, HOST
utterances.utterance: I think Donald Trump or, at least, his political teams saw what happened in the Senate yesterday that Mitch McConnell, I think, was very shrewd in putting forward both bills and showing -- demonstrating to the president that his plan had fewer votes, actually, than, essentially, what they've ended up passing today. ACR, to fight over this for a few more weeks. You know, the president yesterday at this time, the White House was saying we will do a C.R. for three weeks with a very large down payment. Well, the president agreed to do that with no down payment today. So, he, I think, saw the political writing on the wall that for the Oval Office address and all of the way he's been messaging this, the numbers haven't really moved and he's been getting blamed. I actually think that given the fact the Democrats feel like they won this round, they will feel empowered to make, possibly, a compromise. So something like I said yesterday, let's say $5 billion that includes barriers where experts say they're needed. And the president today talking about an experts, sort of group, I like that too. I think that's like some sort of commission --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: That's Greg idea.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, I stole that from Scott Adams. That was a Scott Adams idea that I stole.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: But I think the Democrats may feel a little bit empowered to say, OK, now, we are going to compromise on this if we get DACA, if we get TPS. I also think the other lesson I took from this, Nancy Pelosi is someone I have underestimated as a Democrat. I wanted someone else to be Speaker. I underestimated her ability to win role back. And I underestimated her ability to go toe-to-toe with Trump. And she showed him that things are different in Washington now. And that's what's going to be like.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know what --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: She showed strength there.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- they totally non-sexist -- they're both workhorses. They're old workhorses. They're both similar in age, right? She's been around. He's been around. Bam. So, what are they fighting for? You know what it is? It's like the ugly vase in a divorce. No, when they were married -- when they were married, nobody wanted the vase, right? That's what immigration is. Nobody wants to talk about it. And then they get in a fight and it's like they're fighting over -- they don't even like the vase, but they're going to fight over it even though it's not a big deal. But I do think to the point that you brought up about the panel of experts and engineers, this -- objective group --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- is a step forward, which means for the war, it could win -- he could win this using that as a weapon.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I volunteered to be one of the expert on that panel. What's so funny?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, I mean, what could go wrong there?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'm Watters and this is my wall.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right, we're going to move on. A wild scene outside the courthouse after Roger Stone's indictment, hear his response to the charges, next.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: A media circus outside of a federal courthouse in Florida, today, after Roger Stone was indicted on seven charges including obstruction, making false statements and witness tampering. The White House saying Stone arrest has nothing to do with the president, and reiterated there's no Russian collusion, Trump's former advisor addressing reporters after his court hearing.

utterances.speaker: ROGER STONE, FORMER TRUMP ADVISER
utterances.utterance: I am falsely accused of making false statements during my testimony to the House Intelligence Committee. I will plead not guilty to these charges. I will defeat them in court. I believe this is a politically motivated investigation. I have made it clear, I will not testify against the president, because I would have to bear false witness against him.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: The president and some conservatives questioning how CNN found out about the pre-dawn FBI raid on Stone's house that was caught on exclusive video which we are watching right here. OK, a lot to unpack in this indictment and what happened today. But, Greg, I want to start with you. You have a theory on the pre-dawn raid --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. Everyone is wondering who tipped off CNN.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Stone did. The worst thing that could happen to him is to be arrested in total darkness. His whole life is a spectacle. He loved it. He'd been bating people to arrest him. What did he say? Come after me, lip-tards, which I think you can't say. I'm not sure. But also exposure like that creates sympathy and attention which he enjoys. And, come on, he looked great which meant he knew it was coming. He had a nice polo shirt. He probably even brushed his teeth. This is the thing about these pre-dawn raids that I don't like, I'm not a morning person. It is cruel and unusual punishment to do it so early in the morning. You haven't brushed your teeth. You haven't had your bacon. You haven't done your stuff. And you just need to get ready. So -- this is to my bigger thought.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It gets bigger than that?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. Stone is about creating a spectacle about his life. I don't believe he ever had much of any influence on the campaign at all. But he like to portray it as much because that's what -- he like to portray who he is. His M.O. has always been about exaggerating his influence, I think.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: If I ever had pre-dawn raid, I'll be ready to go.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I'm like -- the ponytail, you know, the other clothes.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: You have the clothes on. So, Dana, in this indictment the paragraph that they're focusing on is where it said a senior Trump campaign official was directed to contact Stone about any additional WikiLeaks releases and what other damaging information WikiLeaks had regarding the Clinton campaign. Stone there after told the Trump campaign about future releases of damaging material. Of course, WikiLeaks has been called by Mike Pompeo a non-state hostile intelligence service.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: So there's another part where, apparently, somebody from the Trump campaign then calls him afterwards and said good job.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: OK. So --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: So unpack that for us.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, I don't know. I'm just reading it, too. On the three indictments he's got like the lying to Congress, the false statements to the FBI, and obstruction. And just for my time DOJ what I remember -- if I'm happy right here, that you lead with the thing that you think you have the strongest evidence for, so lying to Congress. One of the reason I think they have that if you read the indictment is, apparently, while he is trying to intimidate witnesses or obstruction, whatever, like he's saying, oh, no, I've never texted them, while he's texting right under the table. So --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: And the FBI has all those texts.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: They have it all. They have it all.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: So, Dan, I have a feeling you're going to say this is a process crime.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: I am --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: So, but let me ask you a question --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, forget about no collusion.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: The process of lying, the substance of what he lied about I think should matter and is an interesting development in WikiLeaks working with the campaign through Stone. How do you respond to what seems pretty damming in this?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Well, I've been a Federal agent. People lie for all kinds of reasons. They make mistakes all the time. Sometimes people misremember. Sometime they overtly lie because they don't know what the government has and they're trying to protect themselves. But I find something really interesting you've said, I love to get your take on here, because Jessica Tarlov, who I like as well. She is the reason I'm outnumbered (ph) said the same thing. She finds this senior campaign official, I wrote this down, who communicated with a non-state intel actor to be unsavory. Well, that's fascinating because Hillary Clinton actually communicated with foreign intel people, notably Christopher Steele, who said in an on the record deposition that he got his intel from Russian intel. So I just want -- I just want to be clear, no, serious question --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, what-about-ism. I love it.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Whataboutism --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Marie, seriously, do we have principles here or not? Is communicating with unsavory actors associated with intelligence agents a bad thing or not?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: So --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: No, no, no. It's a yes or no. This is really simple.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: No, but you're setting it up as yes or no to try to make a point. Let me answer the substance of your question. If there's an indictment that lays out in detail that a Hillary Clinton campaign official was working --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: He swore on the record --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: -- was working with WikiLeaks --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: he gave a sworn deposition in a court case in London.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Sorry, Michael Steele. Oh, my God.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'm not a fan of him either.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: If he had some sort of communication with Hillary Clinton herself, I'm happy to see that.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Our team paid --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: But --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: You have to know this.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Dan, I want you to answer for this case and not always make it about Hillary.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: I know, I wrote it down, with a non-state intelligence person is a bad thing, but with actual Russian intelligence --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Jesse, can you give us substantive answer that doesn't bring up Hillary but just answer this?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Substantive? Here's what I would say --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: How do you explain this?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I didn't -- I heard the lock him up chants in the background, I found that really unbecoming.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You know, unsavory, uncivilized --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Innocent until proven guilty.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right, innocent until proven guilty. And use your own slogans, by the way. Those are our slogans. And I would not have gone out with a double peace sign, Nixon move, that's not maybe the best look. Would have flipped the collar up if you're going to rock the polo, just a little piece of advice there. I notice that --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You're not helping him.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He also called himself a tri-sexual. Now I found out that means he's tried everything, which, you know, to each his own. That's fine. I agree with Greg, the pre-dawn raid seems a little heavy-handed, like he was -- this wasn't the Waco compound. This was a three bedroom apartment in Fort Lauderdale. They've expect he was going to come out like Scarface and start mowing down people with a machine gun? No. I've also -- my sources are telling me that CNN was tipped off. And my sources, or Lanny Davis and BuzzFeed, so there you go.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: I clearly have no idea how to respond to most of what you've said -- .

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Because he was on Dancing with the Stars.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Wait a minute, that's what he's got to do, Dancing with the Stars. Was he already --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It's the only way. Well, he's going to be on Tucker tonight.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Who was also on Dancing with the Stars?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Nicely done.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Guess what? I'm going to be on Tucker tonight.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Everybody is on Tucker.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: We will -- Roger Stone is coming up, I think, to Washington, D.C. to be arraigned up here, so we will see that next week. See if he's still on a polo shirt, maybe he found one of his suits. OK, up next, Elizabeth Warren joining Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez and calling for new taxes on the super-rich, we will have the details. Plus, President Trump's response.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: As Venezuela socialist system crumbles, some liberals here in the U.S. are pushing the same failed policies, 2020 Democratic-hopeful Elizabeth Warren is the latest calling for a wealth tax on ultra- millionaires with more than $50 million. This comes after Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez's proposal for a 70 percent tax rate on the wealthy. President Trump blasting these progressive ideas.

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.utterance: Well, look at Venezuela, it's a very sad situation. That's what socialism gets you when they want to raise your taxes to 70 percent. You know it's interesting, I've been watching our opponents, our future opponents talking about 70 percent. Number one, they can't do it for 70 percent, got to be probably twice that number. But -- maybe more importantly, what happens is you literally have to study and take a look at what has happened to Venezuela.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Hmm.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Yes, Dan?

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: You just knew. You just -- I didn't have to say anything. We've got a ESP mind language.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: I've just knew it.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: So here's my question for you. You are the representative Democrat on the panel here today. Democrats seem to love this idea of, you know, confiscating money from people, even though they've shown no evidence --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Jesse, gave me --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: I know. I was here --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: But here's my question, why don't Democrats just lead by example, John Kerry, Ocasio-Cortez, Barack Obama, Joe Biden, Hillary, and others, and just voluntarily give up extra money to the government. You can do it. It's not illegal. You can donate. Why don't they do that?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: I think -- because that's a silly idea.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: But why? Why is it a silly idea?

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: Because there's a large -- the point that Elizabeth Warren is making -- and, by the way, she's not my preferred candidate for president. She's probably not my top ten. But the point she's making is raising an issue that there -- the fact that we, in this country, the richest country on earth, the best country on earth we would all say, we still have not figured out how to solve what is a problem with economic inequality. And I'm not saying her plan is the right one, but at least she's getting people talking about it. And the fact that the president's tax plan was tilted more towards corporations, particularly corporations, but also towards higher brackets. There are middle-class people in this country who could use some relief. So, I'm not sure her plan is the right one, but she's dismissing it by saying, oh, Democrats just wants to be Venezuela, or why isn't John Kerry pay more isn't engaging with the really big problem we have in the country. Why more people aren't getting into the middle class can afford health care, can afford college. That's a bigger problem than saying, but Venezuela.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I disagree.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Greg, I know this is a sensitive topic.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I am going to call the --

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Is this a utopia fallacy here, though? That inequality in some utopian planet doesn't exist. Inequality is a problem, so how do you fix it? Nobody is --

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: What's better, though?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No. Ok, first of all, Warren, again, is a copycat. First she tried to rip off the Cherokees, now she's trying to rip off AOC. Come up with your own ideas. OK. Everybody is talking about inequality but what they're doing is -- they're not talking about what makes America so unique in this capital -- this free market society mobility. So, even though there's inequality, the inequality may look like it's stagnant, but within that people are constantly moving. So somebody who at the top 10 percent a decade ago may not be in the top 10 percent, you know, now. And there's people constantly moving up. I mean, I started making nothing in 1988, and it took me a long-ass-time to get here, excuse the language. But it frustrates me because everybody looks at people who are wealthy and they assumed that they were always wealthy. That's not the case. Every single wealthy person borrowing -- people who get it from their mommy and daddy, it's going up the ladder. And it's the mobility that people keep forgetting. The thing that frustrates me, too, when you ask people who are appalled about raising taxes, a lot of them don't have skin in the game. So it's easy to say tax that guy. The 10 percent already pay the majority of the taxes and there's a large portion of Americans who don't pay any taxes. So it's very easy to say I'm for raising taxes when you have no skin in the game.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Dana, didn't they try this before, the Democrats, Walter Mondale, Michael Dukakis, his far-left lurch? And then you have Bill Clinton, the Democrat leadership committee came in and say, listen, this isn't working. America is an entrepreneurial country. Generally, don't like this big government thing. I mean, I don't get, like, why they don't see this as a failure?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And then, Reagan, of course, you saw what was possible then with that kind of policy. I like that we're having this debate because I think we need to have it. As Karl Rove has written younger people who say they want socialism, you should take them seriously and explained to them what this is all about. I think one of the things on inequality is where you are concerned that there will be social instability because of it, right? It's because there's going to be too much between the haves and the have-nots and that's going to create more social instability and that could lead to something that none of us want. The problem is, is that they're using -- they're inciting the passions of social instability and inequality in order to get there. And not making a point, like Greg was making, that your opportunity, though, is what should be there. I think President Trump has a strong argument to make on this case. Arguably, I think, he was elected more on his economic policies than the wall. I think that he had a good point -- he's got a point to make about unemployment numbers. You can say that these tax cuts are for the rich, but you cannot argue that the unemployment didn't get better and that wages started to go up. There were impacts, good ones from his policies.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
utterances.utterance: Jesse, don't you find it odd on Dana's point that inequality is the highest in socialist countries where the socialist - the government has everything and the people starve to death like that's kind of an odd argument to me.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I always say to myself --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Why should I give the government more of my heart and money when if they just waste it on pork and corruption. Here is a great example. The Federal government spent $3 million to study lesbian obesity. Now, my gut instinct tells me this, lesbians are obese probably for the same reason straight people are obese. They eat too much and they don't exercise enough. I just saved us $3 million. So right there, we are wasting money. We have enough money and you can also raise taxes to 90% and you still can't pay for socialism. The universal healthcare thing cost $40 trillion and I know math is hard, but it doesn't exist that pot of money. And if you guys were to raise ...

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: But it exists and for the wall?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The wall is $5 billion, this is $40 trillion, see what I said, math is hard.

utterances.speaker: HARF
utterances.utterance: It is still real money, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And the other thing is if you raise all these taxes you know what is going to happen? The Democrat donors are going to say, "Uh-uh. See you later Elizabeth." And Wall Street is going to get back into bed with Republicans where they belong.

utterances.speaker: BONGINO
